Add to src/lib/tasks/mutations.ts:

  interface DeletePreview {
    id: string;
    title: string;
    descendants: string[];   // IDs of tasks whose id starts with `${id}.`
    dependents: string[];    // IDs of other tasks that list id in their dependencies[]
  }

  export function deleteTask(
    id: string,
    opts: { confirm: boolean },
    cwd?: string,
  ): DeletePreview | void;

Behavior:
  - Build DeletePreview by scanning all task files (same discovery path as getReadyTasks).
  - Without opts.confirm: return the DeletePreview. The CLI handler prints a human-readable summary (title, id, 'would delete', list of descendants if any, list of dependents that would have this id cleaned from their dependencies[]) then exits non-zero. No write.
  - With opts.confirm and descendants.length > 0: throw an error naming the descendants; CLI handler exits non-zero with that message. tasks.json MUST remain unmodified.
  - With opts.confirm and descendants.length === 0: perform the delete atomically. Use the same read → mutate → write path as closeTask / updateTask (see withLock-like pattern inside mutations.ts). In the same write, strip id from every other task's dependencies[] (dangling-dep cleanup). Return void.
  - Unknown id (not found in any task file): throw; CLI exits 1 with a clear message; tasks.json unmodified.

Handler in src/commands/tasks.ts dispatches to deleteTask and formats the DeletePreview for the terminal. Uses --confirm BOOLEAN_FLAG landed by FORGE-3.1.

In src/lib/tasks/mutations.ts, extend the current createEpic by adding an options-object as a 4th optional parameter. The signature change is deliberately back-compatible so existing callsites don't churn.

  // Current (pre-task):
  export async function createEpic(
    feature: string | null,
    title: string,
    cwd?: string,
  ): Promise<string>;

  // Post-task (locked-in shape):
  export async function createEpic(
    feature: string | null,
    title: string,
    cwd?: string,
    opts?: { explicitId?: string },
  ): Promise<string>;

Why this shape: audited callsites — one production call at src/commands/tasks.ts:430 passing 3 args, five test callsites in src/lib/__tests__/tasks.test.ts passing 3 args (one passes 2). Adding opts as a 4th optional positional means ZERO callsite changes — TypeScript allows omitting trailing optionals. Do NOT refactor call sites to pass opts:{} as a placeholder; leave them alone.

Validation order:
  1. Pre-lock shape validation: if opts?.explicitId is present, require it to match `${projectPrefix}-${number}` (via readProjectPrefix()). On mismatch, throw before acquiring .epic-lock. Message: 'invalid epic id <value>: expected <PREFIX>-<number>'.
  2. Acquire .epic-lock (existing flow at src/lib/tasks/mutations.ts:36-86).
  3. INSIDE the lock critical section: the current code already walks every tasks.json under plans/ to compute maxN (see lines 51-65). Extend this walk so that when opts?.explicitId is present, we additionally check: for every existing epic across every feature, if its id === opts.explicitId, throw with a message naming the CONFLICTING feature (derived from the file path — the directory name under plans/) and the epic's title. tasks.json must stay unmodified on the throw path.
     → Important: carry the feature name through this scan (current scan may only yield epic objects; extend it to also return the owning file path so the handler can produce the conflict message).
  4. If no collision, use opts.explicitId as the new epic id. Otherwise fall through to the existing auto-increment path (maxN + 1).

