Create src/lib/tasks/editor.ts. No subprocess / no file I/O beyond the fixture — pure TS functions.

Exports:

  export function renderBuffer(task: Task): string;
  export function parseBuffer(text: string): ParseResult;
  export function hashTask(task: Task): string;

  export interface ParseResult {
    task: {
      title: string;
      priority: number;
      labels: string[];
      dependencies: string[];
      description: string;
      design: string;
      acceptance: string[];
      notes: string;
    };
    warnings: string[];
  }

renderBuffer output shape (one per task):
  - Leading comment block with non-editable fields (id, status, created, closeReason, comments-count) as '# field: value' lines. Include a one-line instruction noting these are reference-only.
  - YAML frontmatter delimited by '---' containing title, priority, labels, dependencies.
  - Body with '## Description', '## Design', '## Acceptance', '## Notes' sections. Empty sections still render their header (for discoverability on re-edit).
  - Acceptance entries rendered as '- [ ] <text>' (always unchecked on render — check state is not persisted).

parseBuffer behavior:
  - Parse frontmatter. Unknown keys → throw with message naming the key.
  - Parse body sections. Unknown sections → throw with message naming the section.
  - Missing section → empty string (or [] for acceptance).
  - Acceptance parser captures both '- [ ]' and '- [x]' lines (text only, trimmed). If any '- [x]' line is present, add a warning to ParseResult.warnings: 'checked acceptance items were accepted but check state is not stored; all items will render as - [ ] on next open'. Does NOT throw — warnings are informational.
  - Trim trailing whitespace from every captured field.
  - If frontmatter is missing or malformed → throw with a clear shape message.

hashTask:
  - Hash over a stable canonical serialization of the task's content fields (title, description, design, acceptance[], notes, labels[], dependencies[], priority, status).
  - Use a simple algorithm (e.g., crypto.createHash('sha256') over JSON.stringify with sorted keys) — this is not cryptographic; it is a change-detection hash.
  - Serialization MUST be stable: same task → same hash. Array order is preserved (do NOT sort labels/dependencies for hashing, since order can be meaningful).

Round-trip fixture:
